# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: peewee-orm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] In software engineering, the **active record pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] It is found in software that stores in-memory object data in relational databases.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Insert, Update, and Delete, plus properties that correspond more or less directly to the columns in the underlying database table.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] The Active Record pattern is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] A database table or view is wrapped into a class.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Thus, an object instance is tied to a single row in the table.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] After creation of an object, a new row is added to the table upon save.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Any object loaded gets its information from the database.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] When an object is updated, the corresponding row in the table is also updated.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] The wrapper class implements accessor methods or properties for each column in the table or view.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] This pattern is commonly used by object persistence tools and in object–relational mapping (ORM).
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Typically, foreign key relationships will be exposed as an object instance of the appropriate type via a property.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] This will find a new `Part` object based on the first matching row from the `parts` table whose `name` column has the value "gearbox".
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Various libraries implement an active record pattern framework, such as POCO C++ Libraries in library `Poco::ActiveRecord`.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] This is a simple example of an active record object `User`, in Java.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Here the `User` class is both the model and data access object and provides `save()`, `find()`, and `delete()` methods.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Another critique of the active record pattern is that, due to the strong coupling of database interaction and application logic, an active record object does not follow the single responsibility principle and separation of concerns.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] This is opposed to multitier architecture, which properly addresses these practices.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Because of this, the active record pattern is best and most often employed in simple applications that are all forms-over-data with CRUD functionality, or only as one part of an architecture.
[src:peewee-orm/active-record-pattern] Typically that part is data access and why several ORMs implement the active record pattern.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A **database index** is a data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on a database table at the cost of additional writes and storage space to maintain the index data structure.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Indexes are used to quickly locate data without having to search every row in a database table every time said table is accessed.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Indexes can be created using one or more columns of a database table, providing the basis for both rapid random lookups and efficient access of ordered records.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] An index is a copy of selected columns of data, from a table, that is designed to enable very efficient search.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] An index normally includes a "key" or direct link to the original row of data from which it was copied, to allow the complete row to be retrieved efficiently.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Some databases extend the power of indexing by letting developers create indexes on column values that have been transformed by functions or expressions.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] For example, an index could be created on `upper(last_name)`, which would only store the upper-case versions of the `last_name` field in the index.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Another option sometimes supported is the use of partial index, where index entries are created only for those records that satisfy some conditional expression.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A further aspect of flexibility is to permit indexing on user-defined functions, as well as expressions formed from an assortment of built-in functions.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Most database software includes indexing technology that enables sub-linear time lookup to improve performance, as linear search is inefficient for large databases.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Suppose a database contains N data items and one must be retrieved based on the value of one of the fields.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A simple implementation retrieves and examines each item according to the test.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] If there is only one matching item, this can stop when it finds that single item, but if there are multiple matches, it must test everything.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This means that the number of operations in the average case is O(N) or linear time.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Since databases may contain many objects, and since lookup is a common operation, it is often desirable to improve performance.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] An index is any data structure that improves the performance of lookup.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] There are many different data structures used for this purpose.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] There are complex design trade-offs involving lookup performance, index size, and index-update performance.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Many index designs exhibit logarithmic (O(log(N))) lookup performance and in some applications it is possible to achieve flat (O(1)) performance.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Indexes are used to police database constraints, such as UNIQUE, EXCLUSION, PRIMARY KEY and FOREIGN KEY.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] An index may be declared as UNIQUE, which creates an implicit constraint on the underlying table.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Database systems usually implicitly create an index on a set of columns declared PRIMARY KEY, and some are capable of using an already-existing index to police this constraint.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Many database systems require that both referencing and referenced sets of columns in a FOREIGN KEY constraint are indexed, thus improving performance of inserts, updates and deletes to the tables participating in the constraint.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Some database systems support an EXCLUSION constraint that ensures that, for a newly inserted or updated record, a certain predicate holds for no other record.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This can be used to implement a UNIQUE constraint (with equality predicate) or more complex constraints, like ensuring that no overlapping time ranges or no intersecting geometry objects would be stored in the table.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] An index supporting fast searching for records satisfying the predicate is required to police such a constraint.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The data is present in arbitrary order, but the **logical ordering** is specified by the index.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The data rows may be spread throughout the table regardless of the value of the indexed column or expression.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The non-clustered index tree contains the index keys in sorted order, with the leaf level of the index containing the pointer to the record (page and the row number in the data page in page-organized engines; row offset in file-organized engines).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] There can be more than one non-clustered index on a database table.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Clustering alters the data block into a certain distinct order to match the index, resulting in the row data being stored in order.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Therefore, only one clustered index can be created on a given database table.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Clustered indexes can greatly increase overall speed of retrieval, but usually only where the data is accessed sequentially in the same or reverse order of the clustered index, or when a range of items is selected.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Since the physical records are in this sort order on disk, the next row item in the sequence is immediately before or after the last one, and so fewer data block reads are required.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The primary feature of a clustered index is therefore the ordering of the physical data rows in accordance with the index blocks that point to them.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Some databases separate the data and index blocks into separate files, others put two completely different data blocks within the same physical file(s).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] When multiple databases and multiple tables are joined, it is called a **cluster** (not to be confused with clustered index described previously).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The records for the tables sharing the value of a cluster key shall be stored together in the same or nearby data blocks.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This may improve the joins of these tables on the cluster key, since the matching records are stored together and less I/O is required to locate them.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The cluster configuration defines the data layout in the tables that are parts of the cluster.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A cluster can be keyed with a B-tree index or a hash table.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The data block where the table record is stored is defined by the value of the cluster key.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The order that the index definition defines the columns in is important.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] It is possible to retrieve a set of row identifiers using only the first indexed column.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] However, it is not possible or efficient (on most databases) to retrieve the set of row identifiers using only the second or greater indexed column.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] For example, in a phone book organized by city first, then by last name, and then by first name, in a particular city, one can easily extract the list of all phone numbers.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] However, it would be very tedious to find all the phone numbers for a particular last name.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] One would have to look within each city's section for the entries with that last name.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Some databases can do this, others just won't use the index.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Then a sequential lookup checks the matching with `first_name`.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] So, to improve the performance, one must ensure that the index is created on the order of search columns.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Indexes are useful for many applications but come with some limitations.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Consider the following SQL statement: `SELECT first_name FROM people WHERE last_name = 'Smith';`.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] To process this statement without an index the database software must look at the last_name column on every row in the table (this is known as a full table scan).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] With an index the database simply follows the index data structure (typically a B-tree) until the Smith entry has been found; this is much less computationally expensive than a full table scan.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Consider this SQL statement: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE email_address LIKE '%@wikipedia.org';`.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This query would yield an email address for every customer whose email address ends with "@wikipedia.org", but even if the email_address column has been indexed the database must perform a full index scan.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This is because the index is built with the assumption that words go from left to right.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] With a wildcard at the beginning of the search-term, the database software is unable to use the underlying index data structure (in other words, the WHERE-clause is *not sargable*).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This problem can be solved through the addition of another index created on `reverse(email_address)` and a SQL query like this: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE reverse(email_address) LIKE reverse('%@wikipedia.org');`.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This puts the wild-card at the right-most part of the query (now gro.aidepikiw@%), which the index on reverse(email_address) can satisfy.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] When the wildcard characters are used on both sides of the search word as *%wikipedia.org%*, the index available on this field is not used.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Rather only a sequential search is performed, which takes ⁠ $O(N)$ ⁠ time.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] To mitigate this, a full-text indexing approach can be used.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A bitmap index is a special kind of indexing that stores the bulk of its data as bit arrays (bitmaps) and answers most queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The most commonly used indexes, such as B+ trees, are most efficient if the values they index do not repeat or repeat a small number of times.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] In contrast, the bitmap index is designed for cases where the values of a variable repeat very frequently.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] For example, the sex field in a customer database usually contains at most three distinct values: male, female or unknown (not recorded).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] For such variables, the bitmap index can have a significant performance advantage over the commonly used trees.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A dense index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every record in the data file.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer to *a record* in the sorted data file.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the dense index points *to the first record* with that key.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A sparse index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every block in the data file.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer *to the block* in the sorted data file.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the sparse index points *to the lowest search key* in each block.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A reverse-key index reverses the key value before entering it in the index.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Reversing the key value is particularly useful for indexing data such as sequence numbers, where new key values monotonically increase.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] An inverted index maps a content word to the document containing it, thereby allowing full-text searches.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The primary index contains the key fields of the table and a pointer to the non-key fields of the table.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] The primary index is created automatically when the table is created in the database.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] It is used to index fields that are neither ordering fields nor key fields (there is no assurance that the file is organized on key field or primary key field).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] One index entry for every tuple in the data file (dense index) contains the value of the indexed attribute and pointer to the block or record.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Another type of index used in database systems is linear hashing.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Indices can be implemented using a variety of data structures.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Popular indices include balanced trees, B+ trees and hashes.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] In Microsoft SQL Server, the leaf node of the clustered index corresponds to the actual data, not simply a pointer to data that resides elsewhere, as is the case with a non-clustered index.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Each relation can have a single clustered index and many unclustered indices.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] An index is typically being accessed concurrently by several transactions and processes, and thus needs concurrency control.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] While in principle indexes can utilize the common database concurrency control methods, specialized concurrency control methods for indexes exist, which are applied in conjunction with the common methods for a substantial performance gain.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] In most cases, an index is used to quickly locate the data records from which the required data is read.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] In other words, the index is only used to locate data records in the table and not to return data.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A covering index is a special case where the index itself contains the required data fields and can answer the required data.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] To find the Name for ID 13, an index on (ID) is useful, but the record must still be read to get the Name.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] However, an index on (ID, Name) contains the required data field and eliminates the need to look up the record.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Covering indexes are each for a specific table.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Queries which JOIN/ access across multiple tables, may potentially consider covering indexes on more than one of these tables.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] A covering index can dramatically speed up data retrieval but may itself be large due to the additional keys, which slow down data insertion and update.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] To reduce such index size, some systems allow including non-key fields in the index.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Non-key fields are not themselves part of the index ordering but only included at the leaf level, allowing for a covering index with less overall index size.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] This can be done in SQL with `CREATE INDEX my_index ON my_table (id) INCLUDE (name);`.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] No standard defines how to create indexes, because the ISO SQL Standard does not cover physical aspects.
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] Indexes are one of the physical parts of database conception among others like storage (tablespace or filegroups).
[src:peewee-orm/database-index] RDBMS vendors all give a `CREATE INDEX` syntax with some specific options that depend on their software's capabilities.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] A **foreign key** is a set of attributes in a table that refers to the primary key of another table, linking these two tables.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] In other words, a foreign key is a set of attributes that *references* a candidate key.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] For example, a table called TEAM may have an attribute, MEMBER_NAME, which is a foreign key referencing a candidate key, PERSON_NAME, in the PERSON table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Since MEMBER_NAME is a foreign key, any value existing as the name of a member in TEAM must also exist as a person's name in the PERSON table; in other words, every member of a TEAM is also a PERSON.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] The table containing the foreign key is called the child table, and the table containing the candidate key is called the referenced or parent table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] In database relational modeling and implementation, a candidate key is a set of zero or more attributes, the values of which are guaranteed to be unique for each tuple (row) in a relation.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] The value or combination of values of candidate key attributes for any tuple cannot be duplicated for any other tuple in that relation.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Since the purpose of the foreign key is to identify a particular row of referenced table, it is generally required that the foreign key is equal to the candidate key in some row of the primary table, or else have no value (the NULL value.).
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] This rule is called a referential integrity constraint between the two tables.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Because violations of these constraints can be the source of many database problems, most database management systems provide mechanisms to ensure that every non-null foreign key corresponds to a row of the referenced table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] For example, consider a database with two tables: a CUSTOMER table that includes all customer data and an ORDER table that includes all customer orders.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Suppose the business requires that each order must refer to a single customer.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] To reflect this in the database, a foreign key column is added to the ORDER table (e.g., CUSTOMERID), which references the primary key of CUSTOMER (e.g.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Because the primary key of a table must be unique, and because CUSTOMERID only contains values from that primary key field, we may assume that, when it has a value, CUSTOMERID will identify the particular customer which placed the order.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] However, this can no longer be assumed if the ORDER table is not kept up to date when rows of the CUSTOMER table are deleted or the ID column altered, and working with these tables may become more difficult.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Many real world databases work around this problem by 'inactivating' rather than physically deleting master table foreign keys, or by complex update programs that modify all references to a foreign key when a change is needed.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Foreign keys play an essential role in database design.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] One important part of database design is making sure that relationships between real-world entities are reflected in the database by references, using foreign keys to refer from one table to another.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Another important part of database design is database normalization, in which tables are broken apart and foreign keys make it possible for them to be reconstructed.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Multiple rows in the referencing (or child) table may refer to the same row in the referenced (or parent) table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] In this case, the relationship between the two tables is called a one to many relationship between the referencing table and the referenced table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] In addition, the child and parent table may, in fact, be the same table, i.e. the foreign key refers back to the same table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Such a foreign key is known in SQL:2003 as a self-referencing or recursive foreign key.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] In database management systems, this is often accomplished by linking a first and second reference to the same table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] A table may have multiple foreign keys, and each foreign key can have a different parent table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Each foreign key is enforced independently by the database system.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Therefore, cascading relationships between tables can be established using foreign keys.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] A foreign key is defined as an attribute or set of attributes in a relation whose values match a primary key in another relation.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] The syntax to add such a constraint to an existing table is defined in SQL:2003 as shown below.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Omitting the column list in the `REFERENCES` clause implies that the foreign key shall reference the primary key of the referenced table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Likewise, foreign keys can be defined as part of the `CREATE TABLE` SQL statement.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Foreign keys can be defined with a stored procedure statement.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Because the database management system enforces referential constraints, it must ensure data integrity if rows in a referenced table are to be deleted (or updated).
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] If dependent rows in referencing tables still exist, those references have to be considered.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Whenever rows in the parent (referenced) table are deleted (or updated), the respective rows of the child (referencing) table with a matching foreign key column will be deleted (or updated) as well.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] This is called a cascade delete (or update).
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] A value cannot be updated or deleted when a row exists in a referencing or child table that references the value in the referenced table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Similarly, a row cannot be deleted as long as there is a reference to it from a referencing or child table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] To understand RESTRICT (and CASCADE) better, it may be helpful to notice the following difference, which might not be immediately clear.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] The referential action CASCADE modifies the "behavior" of the (child) table itself where the word CASCADE is used.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] For example, ON DELETE CASCADE effectively says "When the referenced row is deleted from the other table (master table), then delete *also from me*".
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] However, the referential action RESTRICT modifies the "behavior" of the master table, *not* the child table, although the word RESTRICT appears in the child table and not in the master table!
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] RESTRICT is not supported by Microsoft SQL 2012 and earlier.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] NO ACTION and RESTRICT are very much alike.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] The main difference between NO ACTION and RESTRICT is that with NO ACTION the referential integrity check is done after trying to alter the table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] RESTRICT does the check before trying to execute the UPDATE or DELETE statement.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Both referential actions act the same if the referential integrity check fails: the UPDATE or DELETE statement will result in an error.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] In other words, when an UPDATE or DELETE statement is executed on the referenced table using the referential action NO ACTION, the DBMS verifies at the end of the statement execution that none of the referential relationships are violated.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] This is different from RESTRICT, which assumes at the outset that the operation will violate the constraint.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Using NO ACTION, the triggers or the semantics of the statement itself may yield an end state in which no foreign key relationships are violated by the time the constraint is finally checked, thus allowing the statement to complete successfully.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] In general, the action taken by the DBMS for SET NULL or SET DEFAULT is the same for both ON DELETE or ON UPDATE: the value of the affected referencing attributes is changed to NULL for SET NULL, and to the specified default value for SET DEFAULT.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Another important limitation appears with transaction isolation: your changes to a row may not be able to fully cascade because the row is referenced by data your transaction cannot "see", and therefore cannot cascade onto.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] As a first example to illustrate foreign keys, suppose an accounts database has a table with invoices and each invoice is associated with a particular supplier.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Supplier details (such as name and address) are kept in a separate table; each supplier is given a 'supplier number' to identify it.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Each invoice record has an attribute containing the supplier number for that invoice.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Then, the 'supplier number' is the primary key in the Supplier table.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] The foreign key in the Invoice table points to that primary key.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] Primary keys are marked in bold, and foreign keys are marked in italics.
[src:peewee-orm/foreign-key] The corresponding Data Definition Language statement is as follows.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:peewee-orm/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Models and Fields allow Peewee applications to declare the tables and columns they will use, and issue queries using Python.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This document explains how to use Peewee to express database tables and columns.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] If you are connecting Peewee to an existing database rather than defining a schema from scratch, the pwiz tool can generate model definitions automatically by introspecting the database.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The following code shows the typical way you will define your database connection and model classes.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Create a base model class which specifies our database. class BaseModel(Model): class Meta: database = db **BaseModel** exists only to specify the `database` setting in its `Meta` class.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Because `Meta.database` is inheritable, every model that extends `BaseModel` will automatically use the same database.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This pattern avoids repeating the database assignment on every model class.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Model configuration is kept namespaced in a special class called `Meta`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Meta configuration is passed on to subclasses, so our project’s models will all subclass *BaseModel*.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] There are many different attributes you can configure using *Model.Meta*.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Declare model classes and fields. class User(BaseModel): username = CharField(unique=True) Model definition uses the declarative style seen in other popular ORMs.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Note that we are extending the *BaseModel* class so the *User* model will inherit the database connection.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] We have explicitly defined a single *username* column with a unique constraint.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Because we have not specified a primary key, Peewee will automatically add an auto-incrementing integer primary key field named *id*.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Model subclasses inherit the `Meta` configuration of their parent as well as the parent’s fields.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Inherited `Meta` attributes (such as `database`) are shared; non-inheritable attributes (such as `table_name`) are re-derived for each subclass.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee uses a separate table for each concrete model class.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] There is no notion of inheritance spanning multiple tables.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] If you subclass a model, both the parent and the child have their own tables.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The `Field` class is used to describe the mapping of `Model` attributes to database columns.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Each field type has a corresponding SQL storage class (varchar, int, etc).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Fields handle conversion between python data types and underlying storage transparently.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] In the above example, no field specifies `primary_key=True`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] As a result, Peewee will create an auto-incrementing integer primary key named `id`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee uses `AutoField` to signify an auto-incrementing integer primary key.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Both `default` and `choices` could be implemented at the database level as *DEFAULT* and *CHECK CONSTRAINT* respectively, but any application change would require a schema change.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Because of this, `default` is implemented purely in python and `choices` are not validated but exist for metadata purposes only.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee can provide default values for fields when objects are created.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] For `read_count`, Peewee uses the literal value `0`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] For `created`, Peewee calls `datetime.datetime.now` at the moment of instantiation - note that the **function itself is passed, not its return value**.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The database can also provide the default value for a field.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This produces a `DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP` clause in the `CREATE TABLE` statement.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee’s own `default` parameter produces no DDL; it only operates during Python-side model instantiation.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] A consequence of using server-generated defaults is that newly-inserted models will not automatically retrieve the new value.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This requires a separate query to read back the defaults added by the server.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] `ForeignKeyField` links a model to another model.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] It stores the related row’s primary key as an integer column and provides a Python-level descriptor that resolves it to a full model instance on access.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The `backref` parameter creates a reverse accessor on the target model.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] With `backref='tweets'`, every `User` instance gains a `tweets` attribute that returns a pre-filtered `Select` query of that user’s tweets.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] SQLite does not enforce foreign key constraints by default.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Relationships and Joins covers how foreign keys behave at runtime, including lazy loading, back-references, and avoiding N+1 query problems.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Typically a foreign key will reference the primary key of the related model, but you can specify a particular column by specifying `field=`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] In the example above the `User` data was selected efficiently.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Sometimes you only need the associated primary key value from the foreign key column.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] `ForeignKeyField` allows for a back-reference property to be bound to the target model.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This property will be named `<classname>_set` by default, where `classname` is the lowercase name of the model class.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] When creating a hierarchical structure it is necessary to create a self-referential foreign key which links a child object to its parent.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The foreign key points **upward** to the parent object and the back-reference is named **children**.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Self-referential foreign-keys should always be `null=True`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] When querying against a model that contains a self-referential foreign key you may sometimes need to perform a self-join.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] In those cases you can use `Model.alias()` to create a table reference.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] For deeply nested hierarchies, recursive CTEs are more efficient than repeated self-joins.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The three fields devoted to working with dates and times have properties to access date attributes like year, month, hour, etc.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] These properties can be used as an expression in a query.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] SQLite does not have a native date type, so dates are stored in formatted text columns.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] To ensure that comparisons work correctly, the dates need to be formatted so they are sorted lexicographically.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] That is why they are stored, by default, as `YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] `TimestampField` stores a datetime as a Unix timestamp integer.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The `resolution` parameter controls sub-second precision (default: seconds); `utc=True` instructs Peewee to treat stored values as UTC.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] `JSONField` works across SQLite (3.38+), Postgresql, and MySQL/MariaDB with a uniform API and a chainable `JSONPath` for sub-element access.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] See Backend-specific Modules for the per-backend modules with additional engine-specific operators.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Path access uses `__getitem__` (chainable) or `path()` to extract sub-elements.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Equality on a path is structural where the backend supports it (Postgresql `jsonb`, MySQL `JSON`) and canonical-text byte-compare on SQLite and MariaDB.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] For typed comparisons, ordering, or string operators on a path, see typed access and text mode below.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] MariaDB users will need to specify `MySQLDatabase(..., mariadb=True)` in order to use `JSONField`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] MariaDB and MySQL’s JSON behavior is wildly divergent, so this flag is needed to ensure the MariaDB-flavored JSON SQL is emitted.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] **Missing key** - the document doesn’t contain the path being queried.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] **JSON ``null``** - the path resolves to a literal JSON `null` value (e.g., `data={'k': None}`).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] On MySQL and MariaDB a stored JSON `null` (row B) is **not** matched by `== None` / `is_null()` - extraction yields the string `'null'` rather than SQL `NULL`, so row B is treated as present.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The missing-key and column-`NULL` cases (C, D) behave as documented on all backends.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The default path mode returns the value in *JSON form* - JSON-encoded text (SQLite/MySQL) or a deserialized Python value via the driver (Postgresql).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Equality and `in_` work against this form.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Relational comparisons compare the json *text* on SQLite and MariaDB - use `as_int()` / `as_float()` for portable numeric ordering.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] `.as_text()` flips the path to *text mode*, returning the raw scalar text (`->>` / `#>>` / `JSON_UNQUOTE`).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The API is portable but the underlying engines disagree on edge cases.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This table collects every documented divergence in one place.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Use `as_int()` / `as_float()` for portable numeric ordering, and only call `append()` / `length()` on values you know are arrays.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This module is deliberately the portable subset.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The `BitField` and `BigBitField` are suitable for storing bitmap data.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] `BitField` provides a subclass of `IntegerField` that is suitable for storing feature toggles as an integer bitmask.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The latter is suitable for storing a bitmap for a large data-set, e.g. expressing membership or bitmap-type data.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] As an example of using `BitField`, let’s say we have a *Post* model and we wish to store certain True/False flags about how the post.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Since the `BitField` is stored in an integer, there is a maximum of 64 flags you can represent (64-bits is common size of integer column).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] For storing arbitrarily large bitmaps, you can instead use `BigBitField`, which uses an automatically managed buffer of bytes, stored in a `BlobField`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This instructs Peewee that whenever a query is executed on *Person* to use the contacts database.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The `Metadata` class implements several methods which may be of use for retrieving model metadata (such as lists of fields, foreign key relationships, and more).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] There are several options you can specify as `Meta` attributes.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] While most options are inheritable, some are table-specific and will not be inherited by subclasses.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] By default Peewee derives the table name from the model class name.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] New projects should opt into non-legacy naming by setting `legacy_table_names = False` on `BaseModel`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The legacy default exists only for backwards compatibility with existing deployments.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee can create indexes on single or multiple columns, optionally including a *UNIQUE* constraint.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee also supports user-defined constraints on both models and fields.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Single column indexes are defined by specifying `index=True` or `unique=True` when declaring the Field.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] To add a user-defined constraint on a column, you can specify it using the `constraints` parameter.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Multi-column indexes may be defined as *Meta* attributes using a nested tuple.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Each database index is a 2-tuple, the first part of which is a tuple of the names of the fields, the second part a boolean indicating whether the index should be unique.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] SQLite does not support parameterized `CREATE INDEX` queries.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] A common mistake is writing `id = IntegerField(primary_key=True)` when intending an auto-incrementing primary key.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This declares a plain integer column whose value the application must supply - the database will not generate it.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Use `AutoField` for auto-increment behavior.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] When using a non-auto-incrementing primary key, Peewee cannot distinguish between a new row (needs `INSERT`) and an existing row (needs `UPDATE`) by checking whether the primary key is `None`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Composite primary keys are most appropriate for junction tables in many-to-many relationships.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee has limited support for foreign keys *to* models with composite primary keys; avoid them in models that other models will reference.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Note that `Model.save()` and `Model.delete_instance()` do not work on keyless models, since both require a primary key to target a specific row.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Use `Model.insert()`, `Model.update()`, and `Model.delete()` (the class-level query methods) instead.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Peewee allows arbitrary constraints to `Model` classes.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Suppose you have a *people* table with a composite primary key of two columns: the person’s first and last name.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] You wish to have another table relate to the *people* table.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Schema Management for documentation on table creation and other schema management tasks.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The following sections cover scenarios that arise less frequently.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] New users can skip this section and return to it when the need arises.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Sometimes it happens that you will create a circular dependency between two tables.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Circular foreign keys should be refactored (by adding an intermediary table, for instance).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Adding circular foreign keys with peewee is a bit tricky because at the time you are defining either foreign key, the model it points to will not have been defined yet, causing a `NameError`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Because SQLite has limited support for altering tables, foreign-key constraints cannot be added to a table after it has been created.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Several names are reserved by `Model` for built-in methods and attributes (for example `save`, `create`, `delete`, `update`, `get`).
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] Declaring a field with one of these names overwrites the method.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] The database column is still named `create` and `update`; the Python attributes are `created_at` and `updated_at`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] `BareField` declares a column with no type affinity.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] It is only meaningful with SQLite, which permits untyped columns and virtual table columns.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] For full-text search virtual tables, use `SearchField` rather than `BareField`.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] A custom field is a subclass of an existing field that overrides the Python-to-database and database-to-Python conversion methods.
[src:peewee-orm/peewee-models] This is most useful when a database offers a column type that has no built-in Peewee equivalent, or when a standard column type should carry application-specific Python behavior.
[src:peewee-orm/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:peewee-orm/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:peewee-orm/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:peewee-orm/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:peewee-orm/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] This guide walks through defining a schema, writing rows, and reading them back.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] Every concept introduced here is covered in depth in the following documents.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] Follow along in an interactive Python session.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] A Peewee application starts with a `Database` object and one or more `Model` classes.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] The database object manages connections; model classes map to tables.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] `create_tables()` generates `CREATE TABLE` statements for each model.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] By default `create_table()` specifies `safe=True`, which uses `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`, making it safe to call on every startup.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] In a web application you would open the connection when a request arrives and close it when the response is sent.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] See Framework Integration for framework-specific patterns.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] If you have an existing database, peewee can generate models using pwiz - Model Generator.
[src:peewee-orm/quickstart] For a complete worked example building a small web application, see Example app.
